Thyroid Basics 
The thyroid is a small gland located in the neck that plays a vital role in regulating metabolism. An imbalance in  thyroid function can lead to two primary conditions: hypothyroidism (underactive thyroid) and hyperthyroidism  (overactive thyroid). Understanding the symptoms, tests, and management strategies is crucial to providing support  and guidance. 
Types of Thyroid Disorders: 
Hypothyroidism: 
Description: The thyroid is less active, leading to slowed metabolism. 
Symptoms:
Weight Gain
Persistent Fatigue
Irregular Menstrual Cycles
Hair thinning
Dry Skin
In severe cases, autoimmune conditions like Hashimoto's thyroiditis.
Hyperthyroidism: 
Description: The thyroid is overly active, causing a rapid metabolism.
Symptoms: 
Weight loss
Loss of appetite
Hair thinning and skin issues
Increased heart rate 
Diagnostic Tests and Reference Ranges: 
T3 (Triiodothyronine): 80-220 ng/dL 
T4 (Thyroxine): 5.0-12.0 ¬µg/dL 
TSH (Thyroid Stimulating Hormone): 0.4-4.0 mIU/L (Higher levels indicate hypothyroidism). ‚Ä¢ We have worked with people who have had TSH even at 21. 
Medication and Dosage Guidelines: 
Common Medications: Thyronorm or Thyronoxin. 
Dosage Ranges: 50-100 mcg is standard; 100-150 mcg is moderate; 200 mcg is used in severe cases.
Dosage typically decreases with proper management through diet and lifestyle changes. 
Management and Dietary Guidelines: 
Focus on overall nourishment and metabolism support. 
Avoid foods containing goitrogens (e.g., raw broccoli, cauliflower, spinach, and soy). These can be consumed  when cooked or steamed. 
But when these cruciferous foods are cooked and steamed there are no goitrogens in the foods, so we can  even plan that. 
Include iodine-rich foods, selenium, zinc, Vitamin D, and antioxidants in the diet. 
How to pitch 
It is a lifestyle disorder. Over time the deficiencies in the body lead to these diseases. For example - regular  consumption of alcohol stops the absorption of Vitamin B12 in the body. You might take medicine to correct  it today but if it is not fixed permanently, it will lead to diseases. 
We will work on the overall nourishment of your body.
Thyroid impacts your metabolism, so we will work on your metabolism.
PCOD/PCOS Basics 
Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS) and Polycystic Ovary Disorder (PCOD) are hormonal imbalances in females that  affect the ovaries. These conditions are increasingly common and often stem from diet, lifestyle, and environmental  factors. 
Overview: 
Ovaries develop multiple small cysts, disrupting normal hormonal function. 
Common symptoms: 
Irregular or missed periods
Acne
Unwanted facial hair
Difficulty conceiving
Weight gain or difficulty losing weight
Root Causes:
Dietary Issues:
Overconsumption of processed foods (e.g., chips with MSG or maltodextrin). 
Eating irregularly or reheated meals frequently.
Lifestyle Factors:
High stress levels (work or personal).
Sedentary behaviour.
Physical disruptions (e.g., relocating to a new environment).
Diagnostic Tests:
Ultrasound to check for cysts in the ovaries.
Management Strategies:
Tailored plans depending on the type of PCOS:
For insulin resistance, focus on a high-protein, low-carb diet.
For gluten or lactose intolerance, eliminate specific foods.
Monitor and manage individual intolerances caused by hormonal fluctuations.
Lifestyle interventions:
Stress management, consistent physical activity, and sleep hygiene. 
How to Pitch: 
PCOS/PCOD requires individualized care. Educating clients about how different types of PCOS demand  unique dietary and lifestyle changes will show expertise and empathy. 
Diabetes Basics
Diabetes is a chronic condition characterized by high blood sugar levels. It occurs due to the body‚Äôs inability to  produce or use insulin effectively. 
Types of Diabetes:
Type 1 Diabetes:
The body cannot produce insulin.
Commonly affects young individuals.
Managed through insulin injections.
Type 2 Diabetes:
 Insulin resistance where the body doesn‚Äôt use insulin effectively.
Common in individuals aged 35+. 
Gestational Diabetes (GDM):
Develops during pregnancy.
Diagnostic Tests and Ranges:
Normal Blood Sugar Levels:
Fasting (12-hour empty stomach): 70-100 mg/dL
Postprandial (2 hours post-meal): 100-140 mg/dL
HBA1C: <5.6%
Prediabetic Range:
Fasting: 100-120 mg/dL
Postprandial: 140-170 mg/dL
HBA1C: 5.6%-6.4%
Diabetic Range:
Fasting: >120 mg/dL
Postprandial: >170 mg/dl
HBA1C: >6.5%
Complications of Poorly Managed Diabetes:
Kidney damage (nephropathy).
Nerve damage (neuropathy).
Eye issues (retinopathy and cataracts).
Skin infections and slow wound healing.
Diabetic foot complications.
Increased risk of liver cirrhosis and cardiovascular diseases.
Management Strategies:
Diet:
Focus on carb counting to balance blood sugar levels.
Avoid sudden drops in sugar by eating consistently.
Lifestyle Adjustments:
Regular physical activity.
Stress management techniques.
Proper meal timing to prevent spikes or dips in blood sugar.
Medical Collaboration:
Work with doctors to adjust medication as needed.
Monitor blood sugar levels and medication effects.
How to Pitch: Emphasize the long-term impact of poor diabetes management and the benefits of reducing  medication dependency through lifestyle changes. Explain that while medication manages symptoms, dietary and  lifestyle interventions address the root cause. 

